    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"title":"Task 29","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p>When using the third person singular (<code>he</code>, <code>she</code>, or <code>it</code>) in the <code>Simple Present</code> tense, you normally add an <code>-s</code> to the end of a verb. For example, <code>he wears glasses</code>. However, when using the negative form, the <code>-s</code> goes to the auxiliary verb <code>do</code> and gets an extra <code>e</code>, forming <code>does</code>, combined with <code>not</code> and the verb in the regular form. Example: <code>he does not wear glasses</code>.</p>\n<p>One typical characteristic used to describe a person is to mention that they normally have or don't have their glasses on.</p>\n<p>Listen to Sophie's description of Tom and fill in the blanks.</p>\n</section>","instructions":null,"challengeType":22,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-clarify-information-in-different-interactions","fields":{"blockName":"learn-how-to-clarify-information-in-different-interactions","slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-clarify-information-in-different-interactions/task-29","tests":[]},"fillInTheBlank":{"sentence":"<p>He's got long dark hair and _ not _ _.</p>","blanks":[{"answer":"does","feedback":"<p>This is the auxiliary verb for the Simple Present, but in the third person singular.</p>"},{"answer":"wear","feedback":"<p>This is the verb related to what you normally do with <code>glasses</code> and clothes in general.</p>"},{"answer":"glasses","feedback":"<p>A pair of lenses in a frame. You wear them in front of your eyes to see better if things look blurry.</p>"}]},"scene":{"setup":{"background":"company2-center.png","characters":[{"character":"Sophie","position":{"x":50,"y":0,"z":1.4},"opacity":0}],"audio":{"filename":"4.3-2.mp3","startTime":1,"startTimestamp":18.04,"finishTimestamp":20.68},"alwaysShowDialogue":null},"commands":[{"backgrou